<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-523-598  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 523 598.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  August 14 1989 n232 p32(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Surrealism south of the border; debt, rain, bureaucracy andcorruption conspire to keep Latin American telecom primitive.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Messmer, Ellen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Telecommunication systems in Latin America have been crippled bybureaucracy, corruption, foreign debt and even the weather.andP;  Ittakes two to four years to get a telephone in Argentina becausethe country invests very little money in developing atelecommunications infrastructure.andP;  The absence of moderninformation networks prohibits local businesses from competingwith their foreign counterparts, who in turn are hampered in theirattempts to do business in the local environment.andP;  Droughts affectpower-generating dams and the rains destroy equipment for whichthere is a scarcity of replacements.andP;  Local officials must bebribed to get an installation process started.andP;  Repair crewssabotage phone lines to augment their pay.andP;  Mexico's state-ownedTelemex, which posted a revenue of $1 billion in 1988, reportsthat it receives 12,000 complaints a day and that 20 percent ofits 4.4 million telephone lines and 9 million telephones do notfunction.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Latin AmericaTelecommunicationsMismanagementTelephone Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>